data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, `ThreadAbortException`, or `Thread.ResetAbort` — it only uses `Thread.Start`, `.Join`, and `.Sleep`, which all work identically on .NET 8. No Thread.Abort migration is needed here.

That said, the code could be modernized to use `Task` or `Parallel.ForEach`, which is the idiomatic .NET 8 approach and supports cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken` if you need it later:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, item => Process(item));
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

